	<!-- open content container -->

<div align="center">
	<div class="page" style="width:100%; text-align:left">
		<div style="padding:0px 25px 0px 25px">

	<div id="edit1282523" style="padding:0px 0px 6px 0px">
	<!-- this is not the last post shown on the page -->	


<table id="post1282523" class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
<tr>
	
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" >		
			<!-- status icon and date -->
			<a name="post1282523"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/legacy_images/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a>
			January 10th, 2008, 10:18 AM
			
			<!-- / status icon and date -->				
		</td>
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" align="right">
			&nbsp;
			&nbsp;
			#<a href="showpost.php?p=1282523&amp;postcount=64" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount1282523" name="64"><strong>64</strong></a>
			
		</td>
	
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
	
	
			<div id="postmenu_1282523">
				
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?u=286">Elasto</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_1282523", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Keep calm...</div>
			
			
			
		




			<div class="smallfont">

<!-- Profiles -->
 
<!-- / Profiles -->



				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1282523">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1282523">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Me</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">The thing is, though, the way the tax is apportioned out is a completely independent variable from the total cost. You could have a progressive income tax funding it or a regressive sales tax. That is completely irrelevant.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Here's an example to clarify:<br />
<br />
Let's take the figures I found from that other thread of $4,500 per head to fund the US system and $2,000 per head to fund ours. I know they are from 2000 but it's just for sake of example.<br />
<br />
I don't know how much the employer/employee split is for you, so let's just say for sake of example it is about 50/50: ie that about half the premiums paid to health insurers comes from employers and about half from private individuals and government. So about $2,250 each.<br />
<br />
If you could implement UHC and get your costs down to our levels, one way to choose to tax it would be to reduce private and government contributions down to zero and reduce employer contributions from $2,250 down to $2,000.<br />
<br />
The Torcer family is over the moon, because they now not only have nothing to pay in insurance premiums each month, they might even get a pay rise from their employer's contributions dropping!<br />
<br />
But it's better than that, because of course the employer contributions wouldn't remain as they are today: Instead of some employers choosing to buy insurance as a perk and some not - the cost would get spread out evenly in some form of corporation tax. So a portion that Torcer's company was paying would get paid by a company that previously bought no insurance at all. So his pay rise might get to be even higher!<br />
<br />
Obviously, I wouldn't claim that our system is perfect. We have longer waiting times in our A&amp;E departments and for some treatments than you do. A big push for bed occupancy efficiency this decade and penny pinching in cleaning contracts has resulted in poorer cleaning standards and a rise in hospital infection rates. There are more reasons than just plain efficiency and lack of profiteering in our healthcare system for our costs being lower than yours. Some of it is just simply that we get a poorer service. But it isn't <i>that</i> bad. It isn't <i>that</i> worse than yours. And it's not like the option of private healthcare is taken away here - you can still pay for it - and you might still have change left over from your $2,500 cut to get it!<br />
<br />
Anyhow, don't pick at the detail of my example too much. The main point was to say that under a UHC system, the Torcer family could be better off and they could be worse off. A UHC system in and of itself is not related to the choice of tax the government makes to raise the funds. The simple fact that it is a UHC system should not make it automatic that taxes should or would go up for anyone. Indeed it's quite conceivable they could go down for <i>everyone</i>. Choose to support or not support UHC for reasons other than how you think it might affect your individual tax bill - because you simply don't know how that will be.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				"I hear and I forget. I see and I remember. I do and I understand."<br />
- Confucius
