		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1282578">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Torcer Arcana</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I find it <b>impossible to believe </b>that UHC would not result in a tax increase.  The question is would the tax increase be less or more than what we'd save in premiums?</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
Aren't the total costs to you over the course of your lifetime more relevant than just your monthly costs?<br />
<br />
Compare it to car insurance: You can run around with partial (or without any) car insurance, and save a bundle on premiums in the short term.  But if you ever get into an accident, you'll have to pay for anything not covered by your limited (or non-existant) insurance.<br />
<br />
The same applies to health care:  If your monthly premiums give you coverage, and that coverage is not sufficient to *fully cover* every illness you suffer over the entire course of your life, then you will pay the difference.  <br />
<br />
<br />
That's why monthly costs are only part of the story, not the whole story.<br />
<br />
<br />
(and yes, I realize that you've been playing Devil's Advocate somewhat on this issue, Torcer - and I know that in order to convince people to endorse (vote for) UHC, you'd have to get them to look at the long-term picture, not just the short-term - and that's always difficult)
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
		<!-- edit note -->
			<div class="smallfont">			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
