				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Zarbonius</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Aren't the total costs to you over the course of your lifetime more relevant than just your monthly costs?<br />
<br />
Compare it to car insurance: You can run around with partial (or without any) car insurance, and save a bundle on premiums in the short term.  But if you ever get into an accident, you'll have to pay for anything not covered by your limited (or non-existant) insurance.<br />
<br />
The same applies to health care:  If your monthly premiums give you coverage, and that coverage is not sufficient to *fully cover* every illness you suffer over the entire course of your life, then you will pay the difference.  <br />
<br />
<br />
That's why monthly costs are only part of the story, not the whole story.<br />
<br />
<br />
(and yes, I realize that you've been playing Devil's Advocate somewhat on this issue, Torcer - and I know that in order to convince people to endorse (vote for) UHC, you'd have to get them to look at the long-term picture, not just the short-term - and that's always difficult)</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Well, the thing of that is lifetime costs are all well and good, but if the monthly cost means you suddenly can't afford the house you have been paying for jsut fine for the last 10+ years, then the monthly cost suddenly becomes bigger than anything else.
                  
