	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1282600">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1282600">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>HoranafofPrexus</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Well, the thing of that is lifetime costs are all well and good, but if the monthly cost means you suddenly can't afford the house you have been paying for jsut fine for the last 10+ years, then the monthly cost suddenly becomes bigger than anything else.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
Oddly, that's kind of my point.  Under a UHC system, your lifetime costs are much more predictable, and you can purchase a home knowing that you'll be able to afford the mortgage payments even if you become ill and require extensive medical care.<br />
<br />
Under the current system, if you have a lovely home that you've been affording just fine for the last 10+ years and you become ill and are required to cover the costs that your health insurance won't - you could very well be losing that home anyway.<br />
<br />
<br />
Needless to say, if the US ever *does* transition to a UHC system, great care would have to be taken to ensure that the transition process itself wouldn't cause undue hardship for the majority of the population.  That would be a particular challenge (most likely any tax changes would have to be phased in over a number of years to give people sufficient time to re-budget and/or re-assess their lifestyles).<br />
<br />
Nobody ever said it would be *easy*.  <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Wink" class="inlineimg" />
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
